Macedonians decided in a referendum on whether to change the name of their country
The people of Macedonia decided in a referendum held on Sunday on whether their name will change to "Republic of Northern Macedonia", a gesture that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked their candidacy for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbour is a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slavic population, the majority in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said that he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has questioned whether participation will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
On the referendum ballot the following question was raised: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the break-up of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies such as the EU and NATO.
"Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, quite a few Members of Parliament have said that they will respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that, at 1 p.m., no irregularities had been reported.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% of the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters deposited their vote.
"I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
Zoran Zaev, Prime Minister of Macedonia, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko deposited their vote in the Macedonia referendum on a change of name of the country that would open the way for joining NATO and the European Union in Strumica (Macedonia) on 30 September 2018.
In front of Parliament, in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small stage and removed chairs in front of tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of joining NATO and the EU, but we want to do so with our heads high, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don't want us to enter like Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev says joining NATO would bring the much-needed investment Macedonia, whose unemployment rate is more than 20%.
"I think the vast majority will be in favour, as more than 80% of citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after depositing his vote.
He said a positive outcome would be a "confirmation of our future".
A survey published last Monday by the Policy Research Institute ensured that between 30 and 43% of voters were going to participate in the referendum, which means less than the required participation.
Another poll conducted by Telma TV, Macedonia, revealed that 57% of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour.
For the referendum to be considered a success, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
Should it fail, it would be the first serious blow to the policy of the pro-Western government since it came to power in May last year.
