Throughout Bolivia, a land without a sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to re-sea the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the greatest in decades, as Bolivia expects a resolution from the International Court of Justice by October 1, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will observe the ruling of the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country, in the hope that the Hague court will pronounce itself in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign exit to the sea.
