"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised in late August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did.
The UN agency based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The fact that the decision of the International Court of Justice comes only six months after the closing arguments indicates that the case "was not complicated," said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
