John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
Independent educational institutions in Scotland have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges aim to prepare their students for further higher education, for their chosen career and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
Taking into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can observe that languages are at the top of the qualifying tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students studying foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key competence that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, as a subject, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons given by employers for difficulties in filling jobs were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are increasing, making these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with persons from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically pre-empt competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. Also, it was established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today's children.
If they know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools he may always choose between several languages taught by teachers specialized in this field.
Scotland's independent educational institutions devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "competencies for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
