HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% more new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people in the country are affected, according to the health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people contracting HIV in this way has fallen almost entirely, Chinese health authorities said at a congress in Yunnan province.
Every year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000.
Sexual HIV transmission is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBT collective suffers a lot of discrimination.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that 70% to 90% of men who have sex with other men will end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are because they do not use adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of an attempt to address the problem.
