World Wide Web inventor plans to start a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that tries to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
Inrupt is the latest technology legend project. A company based on Berners-Lee’s Solid open source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people will have access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt is "to dominate the world".
"It has to be now," he said about the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable users to create their own "personal data storage online" or a POD.
It can contain lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in a browser and at the same time.
One thing that is exclusive in personal online data storage is that the user is the one who completely decides who can access what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal training through data".
Inrupt's idea, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to incorporate resources, processes and skills necessary for Solid to reach everyone.
At the moment, the company is made up of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform that IBM purchased, some of the template developers who hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world could create their own decentralized apps with the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a radical change where all of their business models are completely changed overnight.
"We're not going to ask for permission."
In a publication in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote about Inrupt that "its mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new website created on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has played a very influential role in the debate on net neutrality.
Despite even launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
