The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state of the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything found is expected to shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help guide the upcoming conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the Daubenton riparian bats and long-eared browns from the Inverewe gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic property locations to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds that are collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of the calls of bats and which species do.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, expects the results to reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are threatened by the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
but, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and, at times, rescues.
The organization has even opened the first and only dedicated reserve for Scotland's bats in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
"We have ancient buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there are still many unknown things about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop."
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a breeding colony could be destroyed unintentionally and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean the annihilation of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said, "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species on which we don't know how their populations evolve."
