Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The new Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission report shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in and on Pinellas County, low-to-high concentrations on the Hillsborough Coast, high-to-bottom concentrations in Manatee County, high-to-bottom concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, mid-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County, high-to-bottom concentrations in Lee County and its coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in northwestern Florida during the past week.
